post_text:
Warren Township High School will be joining high schools across Illinois by turning on the stadium lights every Friday night to show our support as a school community for the Class of 2020 and the many brave heroes among us: health care workers, first responders, essential workers, students, staff, and faculty.

Warren will be flipping the lights on each Friday night until the quarantine is lifted from 8:00 PM until 8:20 PM. (the 20th hour and 20th minute of the day).

Blue Devils may be socially distanced, but Friday Night Lights can continue to inspire our community with hope and optimism, as they always have.

Reminder: Varsity Field is NOT OPEN during this time. Please do not come to the stadium as we must continue to adhere to all mandated shelter-in-place guidelines.

Stay home, stay safe, and stay healthy! GO BLUE DEVILS!

Thank you,

post_text:
We continue to make progress on our innovative solar project on the south end of the Almond campus!

Within the next several months, the wiring connections of the panels will be taking place. In the spring, we'll likely finish landscaping around the perimeter of the site. If all goes to plan, the system will be completed and generating solar energy by June 30!

When energized, the solar field will generate enough electricity to account for nearly all the energy usage at the Almond campus, saving the district approximately $300,000 in annual operating costs.

We believe in focusing on the whole student. This means paying close attention to the rollercoaster of emotions often associated with the teen years.

To that end, we will offer the Signs of Suicide (SOS) Prevention Program to all our freshmen students in their health classes this semester, as we did last semester. This school-based suicide prevention program is presented by @Elyssa‚Äôs Mission, a nonprofit organization dedicated to suicide prevention.

A special thank you to our social workers for implementing this important program. For more information, visit www.elyssasmission.org.

post_text:
Did you know? WTHS launched an @I‚Äôm First Club this school year!

The club meets monthly on Tuesdays after school in the College & Career Center. First-generation junior and senior students can discuss the college search and application process, financial aid, scholarships, ACT/SAT testing, transitioning to college, and more.

The club considers a first-generation student to be any individual whose parents did not graduate from a college or university in the United States.

New members are always welcome! Contact Mrs. McGahan or Mrs. Hartley if you have any questions.

Welcome to our new Facebook page!

We have launched a new Facebook page as a way to better connect with district families, students, staff and community members.

The page is part of our efforts to enhance communication and engagement with stakeholders. We will use this page to communicate news and events, provide updates, share photos and engage the community in all that‚Äôs happening at WTHS.

‚ÄúWe are thrilled to launch our official Facebook page as part of our effort to use social media to engage in meaningful conversations about our school and the students and families we serve,‚Äù said Dr. John Ahlgrim, District 121 Superintendent. ‚ÄúThose who follow us will receive regular updates on school events, news and the exciting initiatives taking place to continually improve the quality of education we deliver to our students.‚Äù
